  "@id": "ocp:github/lithander--minimalchessengine",
  "meta": {
    "title": "MinimalChess",
    "description": "After watching The Queen's Gambit on Netflix I got interested in chess. I played a bit against computer programs and it made me curious about writing my own chess engine. This repository and a series of small videos I upload to Youtube after each milestone are documenting my progress.",
    "version": "1.0.0",
    "dateCreated": "2026-03-22T02:49:43.483Z",
    "dateModified": "2026-03-22T02:49:43.483Z",
    "keywords": [
      "ai",
      "chess",
      "chess-engine",
      "chessboard",
      "chessengine",
      "game",
      "uci"
    ],
    "license": "MIT"
  },
  "problemSolved": {
    "statement": "MinimalChess is a UCI chess engine written in C#.",
    "context": "MinimalChess is a UCI chess engine written in C#.\n\nIt's focus on a *minimal* implementation of only the most important features and optimizations makes MinimalChess a good starting point for programmers with a working knowledge of C# but no prior experience in chess programming. MinimalChess is written in only a few hundred lines of idiomatic C# code where other engines of comparable strength often have thousands.\n\nThe didactic nature of the project is reinforced by it's open source license (MIT) and a dedicated series of explanatory [Youtube](https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL6vJSkTaZuBtTokp8-gnTsP39GCaRS3du) videos.\n\nIf you are looking for a *strong* C# chess engine have a look at my new engine [Leorik](https://github.com/lithander/Leorik)!",
    "cynefinDomain": "complex"
  },
